Section 4: Strings

Vocabulary:

Key Concepts:
  String Interpolation:
    - When writing a string, you can add variable to be filled inside of it
    - e.g. "Hi there, #{NAME}!" will fill in #{NAME} with the variable NAME
    - Ruby uses \ as an escape character in front of special characters
Ruby keywords:
  # These all do what the name says on the tin.
  .downcase / .downcase!
  .upcase / .upcase!
  .capitalize / .capitalize!
  .swapcase / .swapcase!

   # Same as arrays unless noted otherwise
   .length
   .reverse / .reverse!
   .empty?
   .include(ARG)?
   .index(SUBSTR) # For strings, this words with substrings, eg. "full".index("ll") -> 2
   .delete(SUBSTR) # does not modify receiver for strings; .delete! is available now too
   .count(SUBSTR) # requires an argument for strings
